1: Introduction¶

What is customer churn? -- When a customer decides to discontinue their relationship with a business/product.

We have a data set from a telecommunications company. Every one of the 1000 customers can subscribe to any combination of the different services the business offers, so it can be hard to analyze each customer and each offering one at a time. However, I am here to faciliate that.

The business experiences a financial burden when a customer churns. It is burdening because it is far more expensive to "buy" a new customer than retain one. It is important for a company to retain customers due to their long-term customer value and intervene with customers on the brink of discontinuing their relationship with the business. My overall goal is to help this business, using a model derived from data they provided, reduce customer churn and aim for longer retention with their current customers.

1: Introduction Summary¶

At quick glance exploring the data I notice a few variables that won't be very useful for our model.

  • Cust_id & Region identifies each customer to keep their information organized in this database. Similarly, region does as well. They act as nominal data which are not very useful here.

  • Address does not give us much. It numerical data but I see customers who share address but not services so I can't derive any meaningful reason to utilize address.

  • Gender is not telling me if its male or female so it might be a tricky variable to use.

  • loglong & lninc are two logarithmic equations to long-distance service and income respectively. I do not see how that can be useful so I will not be using it.

2: Data Understanding and Preprocessing¶

Here is what we know so far: There is 1000 rows, each row representing a customer (given by cust_id). The 39 columns are a number of attributes associated with the customer and the business.

Services -- We can see the services that customers subscribed to: wireless, multiple lines, internet, pager, toll-free, calling card, equipment, electronic bill, forwarding, conferencing, and voice mail.

Demographics -- We can see the income, age, gender, region, residence, employment status, retirement status, marital status, address, and education level.

Customer's activity -- We can see a customer's tenure, monthly charges for long-distance, toll-free, equipment, calling card, wireless, and the totaly charges for them as well.

Lastly, we have categorical variable of whether a customer has churned or not.

2 -- Data Understanding and Preprocessing Summary¶

  1. The data was very clean. I did not have to do much since each column did not allow nulls. Many attributes did have outliers, proven by the describe function and boxplots. However, none of the outliers were significant except for equipten which showed that an increase amount of usage caused more churn but the outliers of N-churn did not impact it. I thought it was interesting.

  2. Address, region, and cust_id will be ignored. loglong and lninc are calculations of other variables so I chose to ignore it. Gender only collects whether the customer has inputted a gender. From that, I can't assume whether gender is male or female so I ignored it.

  3. Tenure, age, and time employed are good variables in telling us whether customer would churn. Interestingly, income were on average, the same in determining whether a customer churns. To my surprise, equipment and wireless had some significance in determining churn, although only a minority of total customer base are subscribed to equipment or wireless services.

  4. Three demographic attributes: age, tenure, income will be used. Almost all were not retired so I ingored that variable. Marital, Region, custcat, and education level were evenly distributed so because of their balanced nature I figured that there would not be much distinction between Y and N churn.

    Six service variables: callid, callwait, forward, conference, churn, and multiple lines all had more people subscribed than not subscribed. I figured these are commonly used services for a business that might not be primary factors to customer churn.

    I believe the minority services with more variance might be more telling of customer churn. I decided to boxplot all the serviceTenure numerical variables. (serviceTenure instead of serviceMon since its the accumulation of the serviceMon) To my suprise, I found that equipment and wireless tenures had more churn as tenure increased. That result is different to the other services and opposite to the tenure variable, so I included them. It was only logical to add the equipment and wireless categorical variable.

Q - "Discuss whether the data is balanced or not? Explain what we should do if the data was not balanced. "

The data is not balanced. The amount of N-churn customers was about 75% which could impact the accuracy due to the bias of the majority class (N-churn). One solution is to use a subset of the total data. Using about half of the Y-churn and using that same amount of N-churn, we are upsampling Y-churn and downsampling N-churn to get a balanced data set. Then we split that subset to create a model using balanced data.

Age, tenure, employ, income, equipten, equip, wireten, and wireless on churn is what our decision tree model will be using to determining whether a customer churns or not.

# Taking steps to balance the train data
# Combine predictors_train and target_train into a single DataFrame
combined_train_df = pd.concat([predictors_train, target_train], axis=1)

# Separate majority and minority classes
majority_df = combined_train_df[combined_train_df['churn'] == 'N']
minority_df = combined_train_df[combined_train_df['churn'] == 'Y']

# Undersample the majority class randomly
undersampled_majority = majority_df.sample(n=len(minority_df), random_state=5)

# Combine the undersampled majority class and the minority class
undersampled_data = pd.concat([undersampled_majority, minority_df])

# Shuffle the combined DataFrame to ensure randomness
balanced_data = undersampled_data.sample(frac=1, random_state=5)

# Split the balanced_data into predictors_train and target_train
predictors_train = balanced_data.drop(columns=['churn'])
target_train = balanced_data['churn']

3: Model Development Summary¶

I used the data of 8 variables to help predict customer churn. With the context of customer churn, I am looking for my model to have a high recall in finding Y-churns because the cost of missing a customer who churns is often higher than mistakenly predicting churn for a customer who stays with the company. Successfully identifying a customer that is going to churn and intervening is top priority.

4: Results and Model Evaluation¶

a) Confusion Matrix & Classification Report: Our model overall is just shy of ideal accuracy range coming in it 69% overall accruacy. However, because the data is skewed towards N-churn, N-churn has a higher f1-score at 76% compared to Y-churn's 57%. This indicates that the model does a great job in correctly identifying customers who do not churn.

A significant advantage of the model is that Y-churns has a 69% recall. The model's ability to, in reality, correctly identify a substantial proportion of actual Y-churn cases (even if accepts a decent number of N-churns) is extremely valuable in the context of this data. I do need to point out that the model has a low 48% precision rate meaning the model correctly predicts Y-churns less than half the time.

b) Decision Tree: The root node tells me that the most important variable in predicting customer churn is 'tenure'. Equipten and employ are subsequently important since they are the following decision nodes. If we follow the branch that goes tenure -> equipten -> tenure, we can see that smallest amount of error rate with only 6/64 which tells me that this path is very effective at identifying Y-churns.

5: Conclusion¶

My analysis aimed to identify potential customers in the data from a telecommunications company using a decision tree classifier. I focused on a subset of variables including demographics, service subscriptions, and tenure to develop a model that can accurately predict a customer churn.

The variables I used were decided by a series of boxplots. I had the numerical variables on the x-axis and churn on the y-axis. The variables that had a considerable difference between the central tendency of the Y-churns and the N-churns were the ones I chose. In addition to the box plots, I eliminated variables such as gender, address, and customer ID that were problematic due to their ambiguity. Regarding the service variables, I carefully thought about my approach to the decision tree by choosing whether I wanted balanced/majority-used services or if I wanted minority-used services. The decision to focus on less common service subscriptions was based on the rationale that core services are unlikely to be the primary drivers of customer dissatisfaction. I made my decisions in the position of the business owner who wants to see if key attributes like tenure, age, and overlooked services are causing customer churn.

This approach yielded a model that reached a recall of 69% for predicting Y-churn, a very strong, number in identifying customers at risk of leaving. This high recall rate is valuable for businesses aiming to intervene and retain customers, even if the precision of identifying churners that are not churning is a little below ideal. It is a trade-off that businesses must recognize because it is more cost-effective to mistakenly target a few N-churners than miss out on retaining Y-churners. As I expressed earlier, it is far more expensive to "buy" a new customer than retain a customer.

The imbalance in predicting churn pointed to areas of improvement. A future approach could consist of utilizing the variables I initially excluded or maybe using different modeling techniques that I'll learn in the future. I was fortunate I had clean data because that facilitated my analyses, but I recognize real-data is not that clean so my approach may change as a result. I thought my approach was carefully thoughtout, from the variables I used and did not use with the reasonings behind those decisions.

In conclusion, I think I achieved a very acceptable Y-churn recall percentage of 69% that this business can utilize. The business wants to predict customer churn with the highest correct accuracy which my model can do very well.
